qas.question: Who avoided using the the British model o cabinet government?

context: The prestige of <b0_0>British<b0_0/> institutions in the 19th century and the growth of the <b1_0>British Empire<b1_0/> saw the British model of cabinet government, headed by a prime minister, widely copied, both in other <b2_0>European countries and in British colonial territories<b2_0/> as they developed self-government. In some places alternative titles such as "premier", "chief minister", "first minister of state", "president of the council" or "chancellor" were adopted, but the essentials of the office were the same.
